{% set kadenceInnerHtml %}
We publish guides and recommendations addressing children's rights and adult responsibilities
{% endset %}
{% include "blocks/kadence/advancedheading.njk" %}


<p>The project adds research on children's rights (Convention on the Rights of the Child - CRC) to the AI field. <strong>We create guides and recommendations for teachers and guardians during the project.</strong></p>



<p>The research uses legal dogmatic research to problematize the legal requirements of data authorities and identify AI risks to children's rights from protection and participation perspectives. The legal framework is compared with learners' attitudes and understanding of their rights regarding their data and algorithmic manipulation.</p>



<p>In the second three-year period, the project will produce recommendations for governments, guardians, teacher educators, and educators (e.g., schools) on how they can fulfill their obligations regarding AI and children's rights (relating, for example, to specific AI transparency requirements, children's data management, and children's online profiling issues).</p>



<p>The project examines legal concepts relating to children's consent and decision-making capacity in AI-based systems. It analyzes the legislative age limits for children's consent and demonstrates parents' responsibility for giving and transferring consent to schools. <br><br>The project critically examines legal norms regarding children's consent, particularly those related to data protection regulations. It also examines the requirements for decision-making in AI-based teaching and learning tools, such as what kind of AI/ML schools can use in teaching with the child's consent, parental permission, and the school's teaching mandate.</p>
{% endset %}
